76561198020700030,Recommended,428080,33890438,Posted: 29 July,all,Dis,"Hitting the ball is satisfying and it feels like it goes where it should. The game looks great, and has a clean UI and menus. What I don't care for however is the execution (not the idea) of the energy system. Most of the times where I find myself able to line up a bunch of energy I'm already at 100%. I really don't like how the skulls (negative energy) are placed in areas were goals arn't. I don't feel I should have to worry about hitting bad spots while just repositioning the ball. I feel empty areas should be... welll empty. I feel like I'm hitting more plus signs that skulls but I just hit the skulls at bad times. If I get low on energy, I find myself dying just trying to reposition the ball because it hits some random skull I didn't even see. That is another thing. FoV is pretty low in VR, and this is the kind of game where that REALLY hurts you. The game also requires you to spin a lot which makes the cord wrap around my legs. The cord combined with FoV issues really exacerbate the problem I have with skulls being placed in open random areas because the ball often strikes them when I'm trying to untangle myself or reposition the ball by using open walls that I don't have a good visual on. In other words... it feels very bad to lose. It feels like I got unlucky rather than me messing up.My proposal would be to not have skulls in open areas and to increase the power of the pull back mechanic that uses energy. It would make it a better tool for repositioning the ball, and it would allow you to pull it away from skulls.I'm sorry if my thoughts seem a bit scattered, but I'd like to list more positives. The portals are a great mechanic for repositioning which is the area I think the game needs the most work. I would like to have a better tell of where the balls are comming out though. Maybe the exit portal could light up so you can find it faster while turning around (this would help alleviate FoV visiability issues). Another great thing is the rolling mechanic. I absolutely love it, and it adds a whole layer of depth to the game. It is very creative. I think it can be improved though. Currently, if I hit the ball medium hard it has just as much speed as if I did if I hit it extremely hard. I'd like to see the ball's cap for speed raised. I want to be able to take a risk by hitting the ball very hard. I'm not sure if this is a technological limitation or an intentional limitation, but it feels jarring to me that there isn't a different between hitting the ball twice as hard once it reaches a certain point.I'd like to thank the devs for working on a game like this for VR. This is the perfect kind of game for VR as it is now.It is something that could only be done in VR.It takes a familiar feel of real life sports and takes the fantasy to the next level.It isn't overly ambitious for its medium (too many games feel like tech demos rather than games because they try to make games that are heavily hindered by VRs limitations and end up feeling incomplete)The VR scene would be far far better if more developers had the vision of Racket NX rather than trying to copy normal AAA titles in ways that make games feel more like the husk of something else. I look forward to see the develpment progress in this game more than most, and I'd love to see it suceed so more VR developers will understand what makes for a good VR game."
